# EXERCISE 2.6 (TUPLE): Find and explain the results

t = (2, 4)

# print(t[2])
# Explanation for error: Tuples are indexed starting from 0. Index 2 would refer to the third element,
# but this tuple only has two elements (index 0 and 1). So trying to access index 2 raises an IndexError.

# t.append(6)
# Explanation for error: Tuples are immutable in Python, meaning they cannot be changed after creation.
# The 'append()' method is for lists, not tuples. Trying to use it on a tuple raises an AttributeError.

# a, b = t ; print(a, b)
# Explanation: This is tuple unpacking. It works correctly because it assigns the first element (2) to a,
# and the second element (4) to b. This line would print "2 4".
# To see it work, comment out the lines above that cause errors.
a, b = t
print(a, b)  # This will print: 2 4
